#note this is the kind of scrabble we live for, right? dead even game, deep strategic considerations to make. with the X and Z both unseen, it's tempting to play pretty close, but just fishing won't accomplish that much. I decided I needed to dig into the bag for one of the three key tiles (A, X or Z), and risking the sting of a Z or X play to draw something of my own. it could easily have backfired.
>Charles_Tachi-Menson: ELRSUVZ 14H LUZ +34 413
#note charles's actual rack. fascinating decision, charles post-mortemed this position with Etim and Dennis Ikekeregor for a good 15 minutes after the game, looking for best options. Charles actually has the upper hand here against random racks. he could play SUIVEZ to empty the bag right now and go up 35, which works better than usual with the X in the bag; either I get slowed down by the X and can't go out fast enough, or he draws it and outscores me to win. I think his play is probably strongest, taking a wait-and-see approach, but it also risks really big plays on the right side of the board. Would love to hear feedback.
>JD: EEIOSTX O7 EXOTI. +45 429
#note a great draw for me gives me a chance to win the game fiar and square. I'm playing simply to draw an out-play, hence EXOTIC instead of EXO. If he doesn't score too much, just drawing a 4 for row 6 should win. interestingly, quackle thinks that EXCISE actually has a slightly higher chance of drawing a win than EXOTIC. I went through a lot of the two-tile combos before drawing this play and felt decent about my chances as long as I didn't draw two vowels. He can also win by drawing a bingo, which is not unlikely given his last play.
